{
    "analysis": "None",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv from the current directory. For each file, compute and return a compact summary containing: total row count; number of unique cmdb_id; list of up to 20 unique cmdb_id (sorted); list of unique KPI/trace/log names (for metric use kpi_name, for trace use trace_name, for log use log_name) limited to 50 names; and the min and max timestamp. For error_logs.csv, instead of KPI names return whether the 'message' column is present and a sample of up to 5 distinct messages. Return results as a concise dictionary per file."}

{
    "analysis": "The Executor's summary shows all four telemetry files cover only the incident window (2022-03-20 16:30 to 16:59:xx +08:00). error_logs are concentrated on frontend-0/1/2 with messages like 'failed to retrieve ads', which is an important hint but not sufficient alone. metric.csv contains many per-container KPIs (container.*, app.*) and 1152 KPI names across 59 cmdb_id — we must use metric-first analysis to narrow candidates. According to the workflow, we need to calculate global thresholds per component-KPI using the full available series (the files only contain this half-hour, so that is the global series here), then filter to the incident time range and find KPIs with consecutive breaches. Next we should identify the top component-KPIs that exceed their global upper threshold (>=P95) during 2022-03-20 16:30–17:00+08:00, returning compact aggregates (anomaly counts, earliest anomaly timestamp, max value during window, total points during window). This will prioritize candidate faulty components/resources for subsequent trace and log analysis. No thresholds should be computed after filtering — compute P95 using full series first. ",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From metric.csv: 1) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute the global P95 of 'value' using all rows available for that pair. 2) Then filter metric.csv rows to the incident window 2022-03-20 16:30:00+0800 (inclusive) through 2022-03-20 17:00:00+0800 (exclusive). 3) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) within that window, count how many rows have value >= the previously computed global P95. Also compute for that pair: total rows in window, earliest timestamp of such >=P95 breach (if any), and the maximum value observed in the window. 4) Return a table of the top 20 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) sorted by breach count descending. Include columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, p95_value, breach_count_in_window, earliest_breach_timestamp, max_value_in_window, total_rows_in_window. Limit output to at most 20 rows." }

{
    "analysis": "The metric analysis shows a clear, sustained anomaly concentrated on shippingservice2-0: multiple container.node-5.* KPIs for shippingservice2-0 exceeded their global P95 for every minute in the 30-minute incident window (breach_count = 30, earliest breach 2022-03-20 16:30:00+0800). This indicates a persistent fault starting at the window start and affecting container-level metrics tied to node-5 for that pod. From the workflow, we should now use traces to determine whether shippingservice2-0 is the root cause (is the last faulty pod in affected traces) and whether the fault manifests as increased latency/error rates on related trace series. Traces will help confirm propagation and identify downstream impacted services. Therefore next we must examine trace.csv entries that involve shippingservice2-0 (and shippingservice pods) and detect trace KPIs that exceed their global P95 during the incident window (count breaches, earliest breach, max value) to see timing and downstream propagation.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From trace.csv: 1) Select all distinct trace_name entries whose name contains 'shippingservice2-0' OR contains 'shippingservice-' (to include shippingservice pods). 2) For each selected trace_name, compute its global P95 using all available rows for that trace_name. 3) Then filter trace.csv rows to the incident window 2022-03-20 16:30:00+0800 (inclusive) through 2022-03-20 17:00:00+0800 (exclusive). 4) For each trace_name in the window compute: breach_count_in_window (value >= global P95), earliest_breach_timestamp (if any), max_value_in_window, total_rows_in_window. 5) Return up to top 20 trace_name rows sorted by breach_count_in_window descending. Include columns: trace_name, p95_value, breach_count_in_window, earliest_breach_timestamp, max_value_in_window, total_rows_in_window." }

{
    "analysis": "Trace analysis shows shippingservice pods (shippingservice-0/1/2 and shippingservice2-0) have many trace anomalies starting at 2022-03-20 16:30:00+08, and metric analysis found every minute in the incident window (30/30) for many container.node-5.* KPIs of shippingservice2-0 breached their global P95 beginning at 2022-03-20 16:30:00+08. This strongly implicates either the shippingservice2-0 pod or the underlying node (node-5) where that pod runs. To decide whether this is a node-level incident (node-5 impacting multiple pods) or a pod-level incident (shippingservice2-0 only), we must check whether other cmdb_id (other pods) expose container.node-5.* KPIs and whether they show the same sustained breaches during the window. If multiple pods on node-5 show full-window breaches, the root cause is likely node-5. If only shippingservice2-0 is affected, the root cause is the shippingservice2-0 pod. Therefore we need a compact per-cmdb_id aggregation limited to KPIs containing 'container.node-5' to see how widespread the anomaly is.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From metric.csv: 1) Select only rows where kpi_name contains the substring 'container.node-5'. 2) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute global P95 using all available rows for that pair. 3) Filter the rows to the incident window 2022-03-20 16:30:00+0800 (inclusive) through 2022-03-20 17:00:00+0800 (exclusive). 4) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) in the window compute breach_count_in_window (value >= global P95) and total_rows_in_window. 5) Aggregate these results per cmdb_id to produce: cmdb_id, num_kpis_total (count of distinct kpi_name matched), num_kpis_fully_breached (count of kpi_name where breach_count_in_window == total_rows_in_window and total_rows_in_window>0), total_breaches_in_window (sum of breach_count_in_window across those kpis), earliest_breach_timestamp_across_kpis (min timestamp among breaches). 6) Return up to top 20 cmdb_id rows sorted by num_kpis_fully_breached descending. Include the listed columns." }

{
    "analysis": "The previous steps show widespread, synchronized breaches of KPIs that reference 'container.node-5' across many pods (emailservice-*, recommendationservice-*, productcatalogservice-*, paymentservice-*, shippingservice-*, etc.), all beginning at 2022-03-20 16:30:00+08. That pattern strongly suggests a node-level problem on node-5 rather than an isolated pod failure. To determine the exact root cause reason (CPU, memory, disk IO, disk space, etc.) and the precise occurrence time, we must inspect node-5–level metrics themselves (KPIs reported for node-5) and identify which node-level resource KPIs have sustained, large deviations from their global thresholds at the start of the incident window. This will allow us to localize the cause (node-5) and the resource (e.g., node CPU spike, memory consumption, disk I/O or disk space issues).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From metric.csv: 1) Select rows where either cmdb_id equals 'node-5' OR kpi_name contains the substring 'node-5'. 2) For each distinct kpi_name in that selection compute the global P95 using all available rows for that kpi_name (use the full series). 3) Then filter those rows to the incident window 2022-03-20 16:30:00+0800 (inclusive) through 2022-03-20 17:00:00+0800 (exclusive). 4) For each kpi_name in the window compute: breach_count_in_window (value >= global P95), earliest_breach_timestamp (if any), max_value_in_window, total_rows_in_window. 5) Return up to top 20 kpi_name rows sorted by breach_count_in_window descending. Include columns: kpi_name, p95_value, breach_count_in_window, earliest_breach_timestamp, max_value_in_window, total_rows_in_window." }

{
    "analysis": "We have progressed through preprocessing and metric/trace analysis. Metric analysis showed many pods across the cluster had KPIs referencing 'container.node-5' fully breached during the incident window, all starting at 2022-03-20 16:30:00+08. Trace analysis shows shippingservice pods also exhibited anomalies starting at the same time. The synchronized, cross-service nature of 'container.node-5' KPI breaches strongly indicates a node-level problem on node-5 beginning at 2022-03-20 16:30:00+08. To determine the exact reason (CPU, memory, disk I/O, or disk space), we must inspect node-5–level KPIs (e.g., node CPU load, node memory usage, disk I/O, disk space). First we need an explicit inventory of available KPI names that reference node-5 (and any metrics reported under cmdb_id 'node-5') so we can select the most relevant resource KPIs for focused analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From metric.csv: return a compact inventory of distinct KPI names related to node-5. Specifically: select distinct kpi_name where kpi_name contains the substring 'node-5' OR cmdb_id == 'node-5'. Return: total number of such distinct kpi_name, and a preview list of up to 100 distinct kpi_name values sorted alphabetically. Also return the total number of rows in metric.csv that match this filter and the min/max timestamps among them (as Asia/Shanghai). Limit the returned preview to 100 names." }

{
    "analysis": "We have aggregated metrics, traces, and node-related KPIs and observed a synchronized anomaly beginning at 2022-03-20 16:30:00+08 across many pods that expose metrics containing 'container.node-5'. Trace anomalies also start at 16:30+08 and involve shippingservice pods. The evidence strongly points to a node-level incident affecting node-5 at the start of the incident window. However, many of the top node-5 KPIs have global P95 == 0.0, which makes simple breach counts less informative. To determine the underlying reason (CPU, memory, disk I/O, disk space, network, etc.), we must rank node-5 KPIs by a severity metric that accounts for relative deviation: e.g., max_in_window / P95 for P95>0, otherwise consider max_in_window (non-zero when P95==0). This will surface node-5 resource KPIs with the largest deviation from their baseline and help identify whether the root cause is CPU, memory, disk I/O, disk space, or network-related. The root cause occurrence time is expected to be the earliest breach timestamp for the most severe KPI.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, select all rows where kpi_name contains 'node-5' OR cmdb_id == 'node-5'. For each distinct kpi_name: 1) compute global P95 of value using the entire available series for that kpi_name; 2) filter rows to the incident window 2022-03-20 16:30:00+0800 (inclusive) through 2022-03-20 17:00:00+0800 (exclusive); 3) within the window compute: max_value_in_window, breach_count_in_window (value >= P95), total_rows_in_window, earliest_breach_timestamp (if any); 4) compute a severity score defined as: if p95_value > 0 then severity = max_value_in_window / p95_value else severity = max_value_in_window (so that large non-zero values when p95==0 rank high). Return the top 20 kpi_name rows sorted by severity descending. Include columns: kpi_name, p95_value, max_value_in_window, severity, breach_count_in_window, total_rows_in_window, earliest_breach_timestamp. Limit output to 20 rows." }

